 handling System.getSecurityManager. Maybe dynamic coverage could still be explored with SecurityActions from the source? It's a tricky situation!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining Gradle for Java**\\n\\nI'm looking at the build.gradle test task and wondering how it interacts with different Java versions, especially since we're dealing with versions below 24. I think about altering the Gradle native runtime, but it might not be appropriate. To enhance coverage, I consider adding tests, especially since external runs could be on JDK 21. However, the current report shows zero attempts at covering a line. I wonder if I can refine the configuration to enable the security manager, but on Java 25, it might not help. Tricky situation!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Dynamic Calls with Mockito**\\n\\nI think a dynamic call might still work if I can mock System.getSecurityManager. But adding Mockito seems tricky in a native context because the generated bytecode might not support dynamic class loading. So, tests would likely execute under the default native settings where Mockito wouldn't function. I could consider using a custom policy with a default java.security.manager at the test JVM. But the coverage report could be coming from JVM instead of native, especially since the current test task condition isn't set for Java 25. If CI runs on JDK 21, that might pass!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_S0Kf1jdOVhta4ysZQyaNb8jY|fc_0c090013604f2c400169fc5015debc819fa6f230b774ab154f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"dynamic-access|nativeTest|jvmArgs|runtimeArgs|graalvmNative\" -n build.gradle settings.gradle gradle tests/src/jakarta.enterprise/jakarta.enterprise.cdi-api/3.0.0/build.gradle | head -200"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1652, "output": 1302, "cacheRead": 15360, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 18314, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "